REPORT 6 — Critical Infrastructure Identity Audit (PAM Failure Scenario)
Title: Privileged Access Management Audit for Utility Control Center — Unauthorized OT Access Exposure
Region: Middle East / Global Critical Infrastructure
Industry: Utilities (Power Generation & Distribution)
Author: Ssambra — Identity Auditor & Threat Sentinel

1. Executive Summary
A national utility operator experienced a PAM (Privileged Access Management) failure that allowed a junior engineer to retain elevated access to an OT control system for six months after a role change.

During a routine identity audit, it was discovered that:

The engineer’s privileged OT account was never revoked

The PAM vault had no rotation policy for OT credentials

Shared admin accounts were still in use for legacy systems

No quarterly access reviews were performed

This report evaluates the identity governance breakdown, maps findings to critical‑infrastructure security expectations, and provides remediation guidance.

2. Background
The utility operates:

A main control center

Multiple substations

Remote pipeline monitoring stations

The OT environment includes:

SCADA systems

PLCs

HMIs

Historian servers

A junior engineer transferred from OT operations to a documentation role. However, their privileged OT account remained active, granting access to:

SCADA configuration panels

Alarm suppression settings

Remote command interfaces

