Conduct a full identity audit

Identify governance and technical failures

Assess operational and national‑security risk

Recommend corrective actions

3. Scope
This audit covers:

Privileged Access Management (PAM)

Identity Governance & Administration (IGA)

Access review processes

OT/IT separation of duties

Logging and monitoring

4. Incident Summary
During a quarterly internal audit (the first in 18 months), the following was discovered:

A former OT engineer retained Domain Admin–equivalent access to SCADA servers

The PAM vault stored static passwords for OT systems

Shared “OTAdmin” account used by 7 engineers

No MFA enforced for remote OT access

No logs available for privileged session recordings

This is a critical identity governance failure with direct operational impact.

5. Findings (Mapped to Critical Infrastructure Standards)
Finding 1 — Privileged Account Not Removed After Role Change
Requirement:  
Critical infrastructure operators must enforce immediate access revocation upon role change.

Issue:  
Privileged OT account remained active for 6 months.

Risk:  
Unauthorized configuration changes, accidental or malicious.

Severity: Critical
Likelihood: High

Finding 2 — Shared OT Admin Account
Requirement:  
Unique user IDs for all privileged access.

Issue:  
“OTAdmin” shared by 7 engineers.

Risk:  
No accountability; impossible to attribute actions.

Severity: High
Likelihood: High

Finding 3 — No MFA for Remote OT Access
Requirement:  
MFA mandatory for all remote privileged access.

Issue:  
VPN + password only.

Risk:  
Credential theft → direct OT compromise.

Severity: Critical
Likelihood: Medium

Finding 4 — Static Credentials in PAM Vault
Requirement:  
Privileged credentials must rotate automatically.

Issue:  
Passwords unchanged for 18+ months.

Risk:  
Credential reuse, insider threat, lateral movement.

Severity: High
Likelihood: High

Finding 5 — No Privileged Session Recording
Requirement:  
All privileged OT sessions must be logged and monitored.

Issue:  
No session recording; logs retained for only 7 days.

Risk:  
No forensic capability.

Severity: High
Likelihood: Medium

6. Human Behavior Analysis (Psychology Lens)
Normalization of Deviance
Shared accounts became “normal” because no incidents had occurred.

Authority Gradient
Junior engineers hesitated to report access they knew they shouldn’t have.

Cognitive Offloading
Engineers relied on shared accounts because remembering multiple credentials was “too much friction.”

Overconfidence Bias
Supervisors believed “our people would never misuse access.”

7. Recommendations
Governance Controls
Implement formal role‑change workflow with automatic access revocation

Establish quarterly access reviews for all OT systems

Assign clear ownership for identity governance

Technical Controls
Enforce MFA for all remote OT access

Eliminate shared accounts

Implement automated credential rotation

Enable privileged session recording

Integrate PAM with SIEM for real‑time alerts

Operational Controls
Train engineers on identity hygiene

Conduct annual OT security drills

Implement separation of duties between IT and OT

Cultural Considerations
Your regional experience allows you to highlight:

The importance of trust and accountability in Middle Eastern critical infrastructure

The expectation of strict identity governance due to national‑security implications

The cultural emphasis on clear hierarchy and responsibility

